\begin_layout Subsection
Time Step and Boundary Conditions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{i}^{n}$
\end_inset

 be the set of eigenvalues of the HPR system evaluated at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{cfl}<1$
\end_inset

 is a constant (usually taken to be 
\begin_inset Formula $0.9$
\end_inset

, unless the problem being simulated is particularly demanding, requiring
 a lower value).
 A semi-analytic form for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Eigenvalues"

\end_inset

.
 The eigenvalues determine the speed of propagation of information in the
 solution to the Riemann Problem at the cell interfaces, and the time step
 is chosen to ensure that the characteristics do not enter into other cells
 between 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n+1}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta t_{n}=\frac{C_{cfl}\cdot\Delta x}{\max_{i}\left|\Lambda_{i}^{n}\right|}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Transmissive boundary conditions (allowing material and heat to pass through)
 are implemented by setting the state variables in the boundary cells to
 the same value as their non-boundary neighbors.
 Reflective boundary conditions are implemented in the same way, except
 that the directions of the velocity and thermal impulse vectors in the
 boundary cells are reversed.
\end_layout

